[1] Germany
Date: 1 Mar 2006
From: Thomas Roesel <roesel@lycos.com>
Source: Bavarian State Ministry of the Environment, Public Health and
Consumer Protection, Munich, 28 Feb 2006 [translated by Thomas Roesel, edited]
<http://www.stmugv.bayern.de/de/aktuell/presse/2006/68.htm>

2 avian flu cases in wild birds in Bavaria
------------------------------------------
2 samples from dead wild birds have tested positive for H5N1 virus for the
1st time in Bavaria. As reported today [28 Feb 2006] in Munich by the
minister for consumer protection, Werner Schnappauf, the avian flu virus
was detected in a mute swan (_Cygnus olor_) from the town of Schwabstadl in
the district Landsberg am Lech, and in a wild mallard duck (_Anas
platyrhynchos_) from the town of Sachsenkam in the district Bad Tolz
Wolfratshausen.
"Countermeasures as required by the regulations for wild bird-avian
influenza have been completely implemented by those responsible for
epidemic control in those districts," stated Mr Schnappauf in German.
"Bavaria has been ready for this event, ever since the movement of the
avian flu infection made it clear that it was only a matter of time before
Bavaria itself would have its 1st case."
Now it is necessary to do everything to prevent the virus from infecting
poultry resources. Even if avian flu does not present an immediate danger
to humans, it presents one for poultry farmers through severe economic
damage. That is why there are strict hygiene measures and trade
restrictions for poultry farmers in the protective zones. The EU reference
laboratory in Weybridge has yet to confirm whether this represents the
highly pathogenic type of Asian virus.
The districts have erected around the points of discovery a restricted area
within a 3-km radius and an observation area within a 10-km radius. The
protection zones around the upper Bavarian Landsberg discovery point also
reach into the Schwabian district of Augsburg-Land. All the poultry farmers
in the affected 3 districts have been identified and are being informed.
The discovery points have been sealed off. The 2 animals were isolated
finds; larger numbers of dead birds have not been discovered.
The swan was found dead on 20 Feb 2006 in the district of Landsberg am
Lech, near Schwabstadel, and was sent to the district Office for Health and
Food Safety in Oberschleissheim.
When the rapid influenza A test (by reverse transcriptase PCR, requiring 48
hours to perform) was positive, the swan was sent to the National Reference
Laboratory of the Friedrich Loffler Institute on the island of Riems.
The duck from the upper Bavarian district of Bad Tolz was found near
Sachsenkam on 20 Feb 2006 and was sent to the reference laboratory at Riems
on 24 Feb 2006.
During the period of 16-25 Feb 2006, there have been 733 samples from wild
birds sent to Office for Health and Food Safety. 595 samples have been tested.
The Friedrich Loffler Institute confirmed H5N1 in the 2 samples up until
today [28 Feb 2006]. The Friedrich Loffler Institute has 9 more samples
from Bavaria yet to test. In the 3 km diameter area around the discovery
point, a restricted area was set up, where, within the next 21 days, the
following steps are being taken: Living poultry and caught birds of other
types are regularly examined on a clinical basis. Taking them out of this
inspection condition is prohibited ("stand still").
Fertilized eggs and one-day old chicks cannot be removed from a poultry
farm. Fresh poultry meat, ground poultry meat, meat parts or products, as
well as prepared poultry meat or bird meat, cannot be brought in or out of
a poultry farm.
By-products cannot be brought into or out of the poultry farms as well.
Poultry urine or waste are not permitted to be brought outside of the
protective zone.
After 21 days, and up to 30 days since the official declaration of
infection, any transport out of the poultry farm has to have official
permission. Beyond the protective zone is an at least 10 km observation
zone around the discovery point. Within the observation zone, the following
rules are in force:
In the period of 15 days after the official declaration of an infection,
living poultry or captured birds of other sorts cannot be transported
outside. During the 30-day period after the infection declaration,
permission is required to bring poultry and captured birds of other types
into the observation zone.
There are 20 poultry farms in the restricted area around the district of
Landberg am Lech, the largest with 150 chickens; the remaining have between
10-30 birds. In the restricted area of the district of Bad
Tolz-Wolfratshausen, there are 5 small poultry farms, and in the
observation area, there are 46 small poultry farms.
[Further information: <http://www.tierschutz.bayern.de>]
--
Thomas Roesel
<roesel@lycos.com>
