[2] Germany: bird flu: are pet cats at risk?
Date: 1 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: BBC News [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/4761024.stm>

Bird flu: Are pet cats at risk?
-------------------------------
The discovery of a German cat that died of bird flu -- the 1st mammal found
with the H5N1 virus in Central Europe -- raises stark questions for pet
owners across the world. How easily can avian flu jump from birds to
domestic animals? If a pet gets sick, should the owners be worried about
their own health?
Scientists have known for at least 2 years that felines could catch the
deadly bird flu virus. It was found in 2004 in Thailand in 2 domestic cats.
Big cats who had been fed infected chicken carcasses in a Thai zoo were
also killed by H5N1. And last year [2005], wild civet cats died after
contracting the virus. So the discovery of the dead German cat in an area
where dozens of birds had died from H5N1 does not come as a big surprise.
[byline: Henri Astier]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
